angzhou |date=25 January 2020 |website=The Straits Times |access-date=10 February 2020}}</ref> with the flight returning to Singapore three days later.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Kua |first1=Yu-Lin |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/wuhan-virus-18-singapore-residents-and-10-scoot-staff-back-home-from-hangzhou-on-a-scoot |title=Wuhan virus: 18 Singapore residents and 10 Scoot staff back home from Hangzhou on a Scoot relief flight |date=27 January 2020 |website=The Straits Times |access-date=10 February 2020}}</ref>\n**25 January - No new cases are confirmed with 64 suspected ones. Of these, 29 are negative with 32 pending.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/wuhan-virus-singapore-update-no-new-cases-64-suspected-12337246 |title=No new cases of Wuhan virus, 64 suspected cases so far: MOH |date=25 January 2020 |website=CNA |access-date=10 February 2020}}</ref> In addition, MOH imposes a visitor limit of two per patient in hospital.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Teo |first1=Joyce |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/health/wuhan-virus-only-two-visitors-per-patient-allowed-at-hospitals-children-discouraged |title=Wuhan virus: Only two visitors per patient allowed at hospitals; children discouraged from visiting |date=30 January 2020 |website=The Straits Times |access-date=17 February 2020}}</ref>\n**26 January - The fourth case is confirmed.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/4th-confirmed-case-of-wuhan-pneumonia-virus-in-singapore-moh-12339912 |title=4th confirmed case of Wuhan virus in Singapore: MOH |date=26 January 2020 |website=CNA |access-date=16\u00a0February 2020}}</ref> Later that day, there are 92 suspect cases, of which 46 are negative.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Chang |first1=Ai-Lien |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/wuhan-virus-no-new-cases-in-singapore-number-of-confirmed-cases-stands-at-4 |title=Wuhan virus: No new confirmed cases in Singapore, number of suspect cases climbs to 92 |date=26 January 2020 |website=The Straits Times |access-date=16\u00a0February 2020}}</ref>\n**27 January - \n***[[HardwareZone]] is issued a correction notice over an online post falsely claiming a death in Singapore from the coronavirus. The post is deleted a day before the notice is issued.<ref>{{cite web |title=SPH Magazines complies with Pofma correction order on false HardwareZone post related to the Wuhan virus |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/sph-magazines-complies-with-pofma-correction-order-on-false-hardwarezone-post |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=16 February 2020 |date=27 January 2020}}</ref>\n***A 14-day leave of absence (LOA) is imposed for students and teachers, as well as those working with vulnerable sectors like pre-schools, healthcare and eldercare returning from mainland China, with students doing home-based learning instead. Temperature screening for all flights will start from 29 January with additional checks on flights from China and passengers from Hubei. In addition, people who travelled to China in the last 14 days will need to fill health and travel declarations and monitor health with temperature checks. MOH will now advise against travel to mainland China. Hostels in [[National University of Singapore]], [[Nanyang Technological University]], and [[Singapore Management University]] will also be designated as quarantine facilities.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Chang |first1=Ai-Lien |last2=Khalik |first2=Salma |last3=Kurohi |first3=Rei |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/wuhan-virus-singapore-to-impose-14-days-leave-of-absence-for-those-in-schools-healthcare |title=Wuhan virus: Singapore to impose 14 days leave of absence for those in schools, healthcare and eldercare who travelled to China |date=27 January 2020 |website=The Straits Times |access-date=16 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Lai |first1=Linette |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/wuhan-virus-students-school-staff-returning-from-china-to-take-14-