f drivers are quarantined |date=27 January 2020 |website=The Straits Times |access-date=17 February 2020}}</ref>\n***A patient was taken from [[Causeway Point]] to a hospital after being suspected of having the virus. The incident was confirmed the following day in a letter.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Toh |first1=Ting Wei |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/health/raffles-medical-investigates-photo-of-patients-nric-amid-claims-of-wuhan-virus-case |title=Suspected Wuhan virus case identified at Causeway Point; affected areas disinfected after patient sent to hospital |website=The Straits Times |access-date=23 March 2020 |date=28 January 2020}}</ref>\n**28 January - \n***Two more cases are confirmed. A total of 170 suspect cases are tested, with 91 negative. Several new measures are announced as a result, with quarantine for those returning from Hubei and those of a higher risk, and no entry for those from Hubei and visitors who have been there for the last 14 days, starting from noon the next day. All forms of visas for Hubei travellers are suspended immediately.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Chang |first1=Ai-Lien |last2=Khalik |first2=Salma |last3=Goh |first3=Timothy |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/wuhan-virus-7-confirmed-cases-in-singapore-no-entry-or-transit-for-new-visitors-with-hubei |title=Wuhan virus: 2 new confirmed cases in Singapore, bringing total to 7; no entry or transit for new visitors from Hubei |date=28 January 2020 |website=The Straits Times |access-date=17 February 2020}}</ref> Those self-employed under quarantine will receive a $100 allowance per day, and home quarantine options are available. Hospital bills will be paid by MOH for all suspected and confirmed cases.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Khalik |first1=Salma |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/health/100-a-day-for-those-quarantined-severe-penalties-for-people-who-flout-quarantine |title=Wuhan virus: $100 a day for those quarantined; severe penalties for people who flout quarantine orders |date=28 January 2020 |website=The Straits Times |access-date=17 February 2020}}</ref>\n***The [[Ministry of Manpower (Singapore)|Ministry of Manpower]] will reject new applications for workers from Hubei immediately, with existing applications unaffected.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/health/wuhan-virus-mom-to-reject-all-new-work-pass-applications-for-foreign-workers-from |title=Wuhan virus: MOM to reject all new work pass applications for foreign workers from Hubei |date=28 January 2020 |website=The Straits Times |access-date=17 February 2020}}</ref>\n***[[Facebook]] is issued a correction notice over a post falsely claiming the closure of [[Woodlands MRT station|Woodlands station]] due to the virus.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Tham |first1=Yuen-C |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/health/wuhan-virus-government-debunks-fake-news-linking-closure-of-woodlands-mrt-to-the |title=Govt debunks fake news linking closure of Woodlands MRT station to Wuhan virus |date=28 January 2020 |website=The Straits Times |access-date=17 February 2020}}</ref>\n***NSmen who went to China will be given 14 days leave with all appointments rescheduled.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/health/wuhan-virus-nsmen-who-travelled-to-china-will-have-ict-deferred-ippt-rescheduled |title=Wuhan virus: NSmen who travelled to China will have ICT deferred, IPPT rescheduled |date=28 January 2020 |website=The Straits Times |access-date=17 February 2020}}</ref>\n**29 January - \n***Three more cases are confirmed, with 124 suspected cases negative.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/wuhan-virus-singapore-new-confirmed-cases-coronavirus-12364556 |title=Singapore confirms 3 new cases of Wuhan virus; total of 10 infected |date=29 January 2020 |website=CNA |access-date=17 February 2020}}</ref>\n***[[Singapore Airlines]] will suspend layovers from the next day for cabin crew and pilots to Beijing and Shanghai. [[Jetstar Asia]] will suspend flights to three cities in China until 31 March.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Toh |first1=Ting Wei |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/health/no-more-overnight-stay-for-sia-pilots-and-cabin-crew-on-flights-to-beijing-and |title=Wuhan virus: No more overnight stay for SIA pilots and cabin crew on flights to Beijing, Shanghai |date=29 January 2020 |website=The Straits Times |access-date=17 February 2020}}</ref>\n***The [[National Environment Agency]] released temporary guidelines on disinfecting homes with patients.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Goh |first1=Timothy |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/health/mop-house-twice-with-disinfectant-nea-releases-interim-guide-on-cleaning-homes |title=Mop house twice with disinfectant: NEA releases interim guide on cleaning homes exposed to Wuhan virus |website=The Straits Times |access-date=23 March 2020 |date=29 January 2020}}</ref>\n***[[Enterprise Singapore]] advises companies to defer trips to China and avoid Hubei province, along with travel and health checks and make continuity plans in view of the outbreak. It will also work with [[Singapore Business Federation]] on a continuity plan guide for companies.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Aw |first1=Cheng Wei |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/business/companies-markets/firms-advised-to-defer-china-trips-avoid-hubei |title=Firms advised to defer China trips, avoid Hubei |website=The Straits Times |access-date=23 March 2020 |date=29 January 2020}}</ref>\n***[[Outward Bound Singapore]] camps in Pulau Ubin will be designated quarantine facilities.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Cheow |first1=Sue-Ann |url=https://www.tnp.sg/news/singapore/obs-camps-be-used-quarantine-facilities |title=OBS camps to be used as quarantine facilities |date=30 January 2020 |website=The New Paper |access-date=17 February 2020}}</ref>\n**7 February - The Disease Outbreak Response System Condition (DORSCON) level is raised from Yellow to Orange. This comes after more cases surfaced with unclear origins.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Chang |first1=Ai-Lien |last2=Khalik |first2=Salma |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/coronavirus-outbreak-alert-upped-to-orange-as-more-cases-surface-with-no-known-links-more |title=Coronavirus: Singapore ups outbreak alert to orange as more cases surface with no known links; more measures in force |access-date=14 March 2020 |website=The Straits Times |date=7 February 2020}}</ref>\n**21 March - The first two deaths are confirmed.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Liu |first1=Vanessa |title=Singapore reports first two coronavirus deaths: a 75-year-old Singaporean woman and 64-year old Indonesian man |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/singapore-reports-two-covid-19-deaths-health-minister-gan |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=21 March 2020 |date=21 March 2020}}</ref>\n**27 March - Singapore invokes the Infectious Diseases (COVID-19) movement control law, banning entertainment outlets, nightclubs and tuition centres, and restricting remaining building crowd density such as MRT and LRT stations, and shopping centres to one person per 16 square metres of space, failing which they will be asked to close. \n* 3 January - \n**An appeal by States Times Review to cancel the correction notices is rejected.<ref name=\"STR\">{{Cite web |last1=Kurohi |first1=Rei |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/states-times-reviews-application-to-cancel-pofma-order-rejected-sdp-files-separate |title=States Times Review's application to cancel Pofma order rejected; SDP files separate application |date=3 January 2020 |website=The Straits Times |access-date=14 February 2020}}</ref>\n**The [[Singapore Democratic Party]] appeals to cancel the correction notices issued the previous month,<ref name=\"STR\"/> coming a day after it defended its posts.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Kurohi |first1=Rei |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/politics/fake-news-law-sdp-defends-posts-says-it-will-apply-to-cancel-corrections-on-jan-3 |title=Fake news law: SDP defends posts, says it will apply to cancel correction notices; MOM says party should follow process |date=2 January 2020 |website=The Straits Times |access-date=14 February 2020}}</ref> The request is rejected three days later.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Yuen |first1=Sin |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/politics/singapolitics/josephine-teo-rejects-sdps-bid-to-cancel-correction-notices |title=SDP's bid to get correction order cancelled rejected |date=6 January 2020 |website=The Straits Times |access-date=14 February 2020}}</ref>\n* 4 January - The [[Sembawang Hot Spring Park]] reopens with refreshed facilities, the only natural hot spring in Singapore.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Mohan |first1=Matthew |url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/sembawang-hot-spring-park-reopens-cascading-pool-floral-walk-12232820 |title=Sembawang Hot Spring Park reopens with cascading pool, cafe and floral walk |website=CNA |access-date=4 January 2020 |date=4 January 2020}}</ref>\n* 6 January - [[Eunoia Junior College]] moves to its new campus in Bishan, making it Singapore's first high-rise Junior College. It is also integrated with the future Bishan North Community Club.<ref>{{cite web |title=Classes to begin at Singapore's first high-rise junior college on Jan 6 |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/classes-to-begin-at-singapores-first-high-rise-junior-college-on-jan-6 |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=13 January 2020 |date=2 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Menon |first1=Malavika |title=Eunoia Junior College moves in to new Bishan campus |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/education/eunoia-junior-college-moves-in-to-new-campus-in-sin-ming-avenue |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=13 January 2020 |date=6 January 2020}}</ref>\n* 8 January - The Singapore Democratic Party (SDP) appeals the correction in court, the first such court challenge.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Yuen |first1=Sin |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/politics/singapolitics/sdp-appeals-against-correction-notices-by-manpower-ministry-first-court |title=SDP appeals against correction notices by Manpower Ministry in first court challenge of fake news law |date=8 January 2020 |website=The Straits Times |access-date=14 February 2020}}</ref> The SDP requests to have the case held in open court due to public interest,<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Kurohi |first1=Rei |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/case-against-pofma-corrections-should-be-heard-in-open-court-sdp |title=Case against Pofma corrections should be heard in open court: SDP |date=13 January 2020 |website=The Straits Times |access-date=16 February 2020}}</ref> which is subsequently rejected in view of rules.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Kurohi |first1=Rei |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/high-court-rejects-sdps-application-to-have-pofma-case-heard-in-open-court |title=High Court rejects SDP's application to have Pofma case heard in open court |date=16 January 2020 |website=The Straits Times |access-date=16 February 2020}}</ref> After the hearing, the Attorney-General's Chambers (AGC) said that SDP made misleading statements,<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Kurohi |first1=Rei |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/pofma-challenge-agc-seeks-further-hearing-says-sdp-mischaracterised-its-arguments |title=Pofma challenge: AGC seeks further hearing, says SDP mischaracterised its arguments |date=20 January 2020 |website=The Straits Times |access-date=14 February 2020}}</ref> which the SDP promised to correct later on.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Tee |first1=Zhuo |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/politics/sdp-promises-to-correct-article-that-mis-characterises-agcs-position |title=SDP promises to correct article that mischaracterises AGC's position: AGC |date=23 January 2020 |website=The Straits Times |access-date=14 February 2020}}</ref>\n* 22 January - [[Lawyers for Liberty]] (LFL) and three parties who shared LFL's posts are issued correction notices against false allegations on the [[death penalty]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/mha-refutes-malaysia-ngos-allegations-against-spores-execution-method-to |title=MHA refutes Malaysia NGO's claims against S'pore's execution method, issues Pofma correction orders against parties |date=22 January 2020 |website=The Straits Times |access-date=14 February 2020}}</ref> All parties complied except for LFL, causing the [[Info-communications Media Development Authority|Infocomm Media Development Authority]] to block LFL website the following day.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Tee |first1=Zhuo |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/imda-to-block-malaysian-ngo-website-after-it-fails-to-comply-with-pofma-correction-mci |title=IMDA to block Malaysian NGO website after it fails to comply with Pofma correction: MCI |date=23 January 2020 |website=The Straits Times |access-date=14 February 2020}}</ref> LFL has since filed a court case in Malaysia.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=H. Rodzi |first1=Nadirah |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/se-asia/malaysian-rights-group-sues-minister-k-shanmugam-in-kl-over-pofma-correction-order |title=Malaysian rights group sues Minister K Shanmugam in KL over Pofma correction order |date=24 January 2020 |website=The Straits Times |access-date=14 February 2020}}</ref> [[The Online Citizen]] appealed the order, which is rejected on 24 January.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/home-affairs-minister-rejects-tocs-application-to-cancel-pofma-correction-order |title=Home Affairs Minister Shanmugam rejects TOC's application to cancel Pofma correction order |date=24 January 2020 |website=The Straits Times |access-date=14 February 2020}}</ref>\n* 30 January - [[Mediacorp]] renames its digital media platforms Toggle, MeRadio and MeClub to [[meWatch]], meListen and meRewards respectively.<ref>{{cite web |title=Mediacorp rolls out meWATCH, meLISTEN, meREWARDS and meCONNECT |url=https://www.mediacorp.sg/en/mediacorp-in-the-news/media-releases/mediacorp-rolls-out-mewatch-melisten-merewards-and-meconnect-12369778 |website=Mediacorp |accessdate=30 January 2020 |date=30 January 2020}}</ref>\n* 31 January - \n**The first stage of the [[Thomson\u2013East Coast MRT line]] (spanning from [[Woodlands North MRT station|Woodlands North]] to [[Woodlands South MRT station|Woodlands South]]) opens.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Liu |first1=Vanessa |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/transport/first-three-stations-of-thomson-east-coast-line-to-begin-service-on-jan-31-free |title=First three stations of Thomson-East Coast Line to begin service on Jan 31; free travel for commuters for three days |website=The Straits Times |access-date=11 December 2019 |date=11 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Wong |first1=Kai Yi |title=3 stations on Thomson-East Coast Line begin operations |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/transport/3-stations-on-thomson-east-coast-line-begin-operations |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=15 January 2020 |date=31 January 2020}}</ref> In addition, a new MRT map is rolled out at all stations with the [[Circle MRT line]] as a focus.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/new-mrt-network-map-be-rolled-out-all-stations-jan-31 |title=New MRT network map to be rolled out at all stations by Jan 31 |website=Today |access-date=11 December 2019 |date=11 December 2019}}</ref>\n**[[Cold Stone Creamery]] closes after being in Singapore for 10 years.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Quek |first1=Eunice |title=Cold Stone Creamery exits Singapore on Jan 31 |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/lifestyle/food/cold-stone-creamery-exits-singapore-on-jan-31 |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=15 January 2020 |date=3 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n===February===\n* 5 February - The Singapore Democratic Party lost the appeal, with the court ruling that a statement has to be proven false by the Government after a correction is issued.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Tham |first1=Yuen-C |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/first-court-challenge-against-fake-news-law-fails-high-court-dismisses-sdps-appeal |title=First court challenge against fake news law fails; High Court dismisses SDP's appeal |date=5 February 2020 |website=The Straits Times |access-date=14 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n===March===\n* 10 March - An extension of the [[Cross Island MRT line]] is announced. Spanning {{Convert|7.3|km|miles|abbr=in}} from [[Pasir Ris MRT station|Pasir Ris]] to [[Punggol MRT/LRT station|Punggol]], the four-station extension will be completed by 2031.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Wong |first1=Kai Yi |title=Punggol residents to get four more train stations by 2031 |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/transport/punggol-residents-to-get-four-more-train-stations-by-2031 |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=10 March 2020 |date=10 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/punggol-extension-cross-island-line-mrt-stations-construction-12521038|title=Punggol extension on Cross Island Line to begin construction in 2022|website=CNA|language=en|access-date=2020-03-10| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310042859/https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/punggol-extension-cross-island-line-mrt-stations-construction-12521038| archive-date=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n* 13 March - [[2020 Singaporean general election|General Elections]]: The [[List of Singaporean electoral divisions|Electoral Boundaries Review Committee report]] is released. The 14th parliament will consist of 93 members from 31 constituencies (14 Single Member Constituencies and 17 Group Representation Constituencies), up from 89 seats from the current 29 constituencies. In addition, six-member GRCs will be abolished, with the maximum being five MPs in each GRC.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Sim |first1=Royston |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/politics/singapore-ge-new-electoral-boundaries-announced-14-smcs-17-grcs-in-next-election |title=Singapore GE: New electoral boundaries announced; 14 SMCs, 17 GRCs in next election |website=The Straits Times |access-date=13 March 2020 |date=13 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/general-election-ebrc-electoral-boundaries-grc-smc-12535200|title=More electoral divisions, no 6-member GRCs in coming election: EBRC report|website=CNA|language=en|access-date=13 March 2020|date=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n* 31 March - [[Liang Court]] ceases operation.\n\n===Predicted and scheduled events===\n* 9 June - [[Lotte Corporation|Lotte Duty Free]] will take over [[DFS Group]]'s [[Changi Airport]] liquor and tobacco stores<ref>{{cite web |last1=Ang |first1=Prisca |url=http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/lotte-duty-free-to-take-over-dfs-liquor-and-tobacco-stores-in-changi-airport-from-june |title=Lotte Duty Free to take over DFS liquor and tobacco stores in Changi Airport from June 2020 |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=25 October 2019 |date=24 October 2019}}</ref> as the latter ends its 39-year tenancy due to a challenging environment.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Heng |first1=Melissa |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/transport/dfs-pulls-out-of-changi-airports-liquor-tobacco-business-all-stores-to-shut-in |title=DFS stores in Changi Airport to close in June 2020; South Korea's Shilla and Lotte among 3 new bidders |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=25 October 2019 |date=27 August 2019}}</ref>\n* Kallang Polyclinic, connected to Kwong Wai Shiu Hospital will open.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Baharudin |first1=Hariz |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/kwong-wai-shiu-hospital-nursing-home-opens-after-100m-facelift |title=Kwong Wai Shiu Hospital nursing home opens after $96m facelift |website=The Straits Times |access-date=7 July 2019 |date=6 October 2018}}</ref> \n* The second stage of the [[Thomson\u2013East Coast MRT line]] (spanning from [[Springleaf MRT station|Springleaf]] to [[Caldecott MRT station|Caldecott]]) will open.\n*[[2020 Singaporean general election]]\n\n==Deaths==\n* 1 January - [[Ng Jui Ping]], former [[Chief of Defence Force (Singapore)|Chief of Defence Force]] (b. 1948).<ref>{{cite news|url = https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/singapores-second-chief-of-defence-force-ng-jui-ping-dies-at-71|title = Singapore's second Chief of Defence Force Ng Jui Ping dies at 71|work = [[The Straits Times]]|date = 1 January 2020|accessdate = 1 January 2020|last = Menon|first = Malavika}}</ref>\n* 9 January -\n**[[Jo Heng]], lyricist (b. 1960).<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Ang |first1=Benson |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/lifestyle/entertainment/xinyao-lyricist-jo-heng-who-wrote-lyrics-for-singers-like-jacky-cheung-and |title=Xinyao lyricist Jo Heng, who wrote lyrics for singers like Jacky Cheung and Eric Moo, dies at 59 |date=9 January 2020 |website=The Straits Times |access-date=24 January 2020}}</ref>\n**[[Yong Pung How]] - 2nd [[Chief Justice of Singapore]] (b. 1926).<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lum |first1=Selina |title=Singapore's former chief justice Yong Pung How dies, aged 93 |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/former-chief-justice-yong-pung-how-dies-he-was-93 |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=9 January 2019 |date=9 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Years in Singapore}}\n{{Year in Asia |2020}}\n\n[[Category:2020 in Singapore]]\n[[Category:2020s in Singapore]]\n[[Category:Years of the 21st century in Singapore]]\n[[Category:2020 in Asia|Singapore]]\n[[Category:2020 by country|Singapore]]\n", "name_user": "TheGreatSG'rean", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eMarch", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_in_Singapore"}
